===Pronunciation===
* {{a|RP|GA}} {{IPA|en|/bɛɡ/}}
* {{audio|en|En-us-beg.ogg|Audio (GA)}}
* {{rhymes|en|ɛɡ|s=1}}

===Etymology 1===
{{inh+|en|enm|beggen}}, of uncertain origin, possibly from {{der|en|ang|*becgian}}, {{m|ang|*bedcian}}, {{glossary|syncopated}} variants of {{m|ang|bedecian||to beg}}, from {{inh|en|gem-pro|*bedagô||petitioner; requestor; beggar}}, from {{m|gem-pro|*bedą}}, {{m|gem-pro|*bedō||prayer; request}}. Compare {{cog|frr|bēdagi||to pray}}, {{cog|got|𐌱𐌹𐌳𐌰𐌲𐍅𐌰||beggar}}, {{cog|ang|biddan||to ask}}. More at {{l|en|bid}}, {{l|en|bead}}. See {{cog|nb|be||beg, ask}}.

====Verb====
{{en-verb}}

# {{lb|en|intransitive}} To [[request#Verb|request]] the [[help#Noun|help]] of someone, often in the form of [[money]].
#: {{ux|en|He '''begged''' on the street corner from passers-by.}}
# {{lb|en|transitive}} To [[plead]] with someone for help, a [[favor#Noun|favor]], etc.; to [[entreat]].
#: {{synonyms|en|supplicate}}
#: {{ux|en|I '''beg''' your pardon. I didn’t mean to cause offence.}}
#: {{ux|en|He '''begged''' her to go to the prom with him.}}
#* {{RQ:Shakespeare All's Well|I|iii|passage=you do '''beg''' your good will in this case.}}
#* {{RQ:KJV|Matthew|27|58}}
#*: [Joseph] '''begged''' the body of Jesus.
#* '''1898''', {{w|J. Meade Falkner}}, {{w|Moonfleet}} Chapter 5
#*: But that same day came Sam Tewkesbury to the Why Not? about nightfall, and '''begged''' a glass of rum, being, as he said, 'all of a shake' [...]
# {{lb|en|transitive}} ''In the phrase'' ''{{l|en|beg the question}}'': to [[assume]].
# {{lb|en|transitive|proscribed}} ''In the phrase'' ''{{l|en|beg the question}}'': to [[raise#Verb|raise]] (a [[question#Noun|question]]).
#: {{antonyms|en|set aside}}
# {{lb|en|transitive|law|obsolete}} To ask to be [[appoint]]ed [[guardian]] for, or to ask to have a guardian appointed for.
#* '''a. 1612''', {{w|John Harington (writer)|John Harington}}, ''Epigrams''
#*: Else some will '''beg''' thee, in the court of wards.

